# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: glen-o-dee-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Lamont University Professor, and professor of economics and philosophy, at Harvard University.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He previously served as master of Trinity College at the University of Cambridge.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1999, he received India's highest civilian honour, Bharat Ratna, for his contribution to welfare economics.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The German Publishers and Booksellers Association awarded him the 2020 Peace Prize of the German Book Trade for his pioneering scholarship addressing issues of global justice and combating social inequality in education and healthcare.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Amartya Sen was born on 3 November 1933 in a Bengali Baidya family in Santiniketan, Bengal, British India.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The first Asian to win a Nobel Prize, the polymath and writer Rabindranath Tagore, gave Amartya Sen his name (Bengali: অমর্ত্য, romanized: *ômorto*, lit.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's family was from Wari and Manikganj, Dhaka, both in present-day Bangladesh.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] His father, Ashutosh Sen, was a professor of chemistry at Dhaka University, then the development commissioner in Delhi, and then chairman of the West Bengal Public Service Commission.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen moved with his family to West Bengal in 1945.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's mother, Amita Sen, was the daughter of Kshiti Mohan Sen, the eminent Sanskritist and scholar of ancient and medieval India.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's maternal grandfather was a close associate of Tagore.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen served as the second vice-chancellor of Visva Bharati University from 1953 to 1954.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen began his school education at St Gregory's School in Dhaka in 1940.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In the fall of 1941, he was admitted to Patha Bhavana, Santiniketan, where he completed his school education.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The school had many progressive features, such as a distaste for examinations or competitive testing.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In addition, the school stressed cultural diversity and embraced cultural influences from the rest of the world.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1951, he went to Presidency College, Calcutta, where he earned a BA in economics with First in the First Class, with a minor in mathematics, as a graduating student of the University of Calcutta.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] While at Presidency, Sen was diagnosed with oral cancer and given a 15 per cent chance of living five years.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] With radiation treatment, he survived, and in 1953 he moved to Trinity College, Cambridge, where he earned a second BA in economics in 1955 with a first class, topping the list as well.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] At this time, he was elected president of the Cambridge Majlis.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] While Sen was officially a PhD student at Cambridge (though he had finished his research in 1955–56), he was offered the position of First-Professor and First-Head of the Economics Department of the newly created Jadavpur University in Calcutta.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Appointed to the position at age 22, he is still the youngest chairman to have headed the Department of Economics.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He served in that position, starting the new Economics Department, from 1956 to 1958.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Meanwhile, Sen was elected to a Prize Fellowship at Trinity College, which gave him four years to study any subject; he made the decision to study philosophy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] One of the books he was most interested in was Kenneth Arrow's *Social Choice and Individual Values*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In Cambridge, there were major debates between supporters of Keynesian economics, and the neo-classical economists who were sceptical of Keynes.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Because of a lack of enthusiasm for social choice theory in both Trinity and Cambridge, Sen chose a different subject for his PhD thesis, which was on "The Choice of Techniques" in 1959.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The work had been completed earlier, except for advice from his adjunct supervisor in India, A.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Dasgupta, given to Sen while teaching and revising his work at Jadavpur, under the supervision of the "brilliant but vigorously intolerant" post-Keynesian Joan Robinson.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Quentin Skinner notes that Sen was a member of the secret society Cambridge Apostles during his time at Cambridge.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] During 1960–61, Amartya Sen visited the Massachusetts Institute of Technology on leave from Trinity College.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's work on 'Choice of Techniques' complemented that of Maurice Dobb.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In a developing country, the Dobb-Sen strategy relied on maximising investible surpluses, maintaining constant real wages, and using the entire increase in labour productivity, due to technological change, to raise the rate of accumulation.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In other words, workers were expected to demand no improvement in their standard of living despite having become more productive.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's papers in the late 1960s and early 1970s helped develop the theory of social choice, which first came to prominence in the work by the American economist Kenneth Arrow.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Arrow had most famously shown that when voters have three or more distinct alternatives (options), any ranked order voting system will, in at least some situations, inevitably conflict with what many assume to be basic democratic norms.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's contribution to the literature was to show under what conditions Arrow's impossibility theorem applied, as well as to extend and enrich the theory of social choice, informed by his interests in the history of economic thought and philosophy.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Pareto efficiency dictates that if every individual in a society prefers option A to option B, the society as a whole should also prefer A.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Minimal liberalism suggests that individuals should have the decisive right to make choices in purely personal matters, such as what to read or how to dress.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen illustrated the result using a hypothetical example involving two individuals ("Lewd" and "Prude") and three social states: one person reading a particular book, the other reading, or neither reading.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Prude thinks that the book is indecent and that it should be disposed of, unread.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] However, if someone must read it, Prude would prefer to read it rather than Lewd since Prude thinks it would be even worse for someone to read and enjoy the book rather than read it in disgust.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Given these preferences of the two individuals in the society, a social planner must decide what to do.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Should the planner force Lewd to read the book, force Prude to read the book, or let it go unread?
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Under this decisiveness assignment, society would generate cyclic collective preferences, violating acyclicity (or transitivity) of social ordering.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] This paradox, now known as the "liberal paradox," demonstrates a conflict between individual rights and social efficiency: ensuring minimal individual liberty may force the violation of Pareto-style aggregation consistency.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1981, Sen published *Poverty and Famines: An Essay on Entitlement and Deprivation* (1981), a book in which he argued that famine occurs not only from a lack of food, but from inequalities built into mechanisms for distributing food.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen also argued that the Bengal famine was caused by an urban economic boom that raised food prices, thereby causing millions of rural workers to starve to death when their wages did not keep up.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1999 he wrote, "No famine has ever taken place ... in a functioning democracy".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In addition to his important work on the causes of famines, Sen's work in the field of development economics has had considerable influence on the formulation of the "Human Development Report", published by the United Nations Development Programme.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] This annual publication that ranks countries on a variety of economic and social indicators owes much to the contributions by Sen, among other social choice theorists, in the area of economic measurement of poverty and inequality.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen's revolutionary contribution to development economics and social indicators is the concept of "capability" developed in his article "Equality of What?".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He argues that governments should be measured against the concrete capabilities of their citizens.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] This is because top-down development will always trump human rights as long as the definition of terms remains in doubt (is a "right" something that must be provided or something that simply cannot be taken away?).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] For instance, in the United States, citizens have a right to vote.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] For citizens to have a capacity to vote, they first must have "functionings".
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] These "functionings" can range from the very broad, such as the availability of education, to the very specific, such as transportation to the polls.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Only when such barriers are removed can the citizen truly be said to act out of personal choice.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] It is up to the individual society to make the list of minimum capabilities guaranteed by that society.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] For an example of the "capabilities approach" in practice, see Martha Nussbaum's *Women and Human Development*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He wrote a controversial article in *The New York Review of Books* entitled "More Than 100 Million Women Are Missing" (see Missing women of Asia), analysing the mortality impact of unequal rights between the genders in the developing world, particularly Asia.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Other studies, including one by Emily Oster, had argued that this is an overestimation, though Oster has since then recanted her conclusions.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1999, Sen further advanced and redefined the capability approach in his book *Development as Freedom*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen argued that development should be viewed as an effort to advance the real freedoms that individuals enjoy, rather than simply focusing on metrics such as GDP or income-per-capita.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen was inspired by violent acts he had witnessed as a child leading up to the Partition of India in 1947.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] One morning, a Muslim daily labourer named Kader Mia stumbled through the rear gate of Sen's family home, bleeding from a knife wound in his back.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Because of his extreme poverty, he had come to Sen's primarily Hindu neighbourhood searching for work; his choices were the starvation of his family or the risk of death in coming to the neighbourhood.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The price of Kader Mia's economic unfreedom was his death.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Kader Mia need not have come to a hostile area in search of income in those troubled times if his family could have managed without it.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] This experience led Sen to begin thinking about economic unfreedom from a young age.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In *Development as Freedom*, Sen outlined five specific types of freedoms: political freedoms, economic facilities, social opportunities, transparency guarantees, and protective security.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Political freedoms refer to the ability of the people to have a voice in government and to be able to scrutinise the authorities.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Economic facilities concern both the resources within the market and the market mechanism itself.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Any focus on income and wealth in the country would serve to increase the economic facilities for the people.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Social opportunities deal with the establishments that provide benefits like healthcare or education for the populace, allowing individuals to live better lives.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Transparency guarantees allow individuals to interact with some degree of trust and knowledge of the interaction.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Protective security is the system of social safety nets that prevents a group affected by poverty from being subjected to terrible misery.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Development encompassing non-economic areas, Sen argues, renders the notion of a dichotomy between "freedom" and "development," as implied by the concept of Asian values, meaningless and disingenuous.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Before Sen's work, these had been viewed as only the ends of development; luxuries afforded to countries that focus on increasing income.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] However, Sen argued that the increase in real freedoms should be both the ends and the means of development.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He elaborates upon this by illustrating the closely interconnected natures of the five main freedoms as he believes that expansion of one of those freedoms can lead to expansion in another one as well.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] A comparison is also drawn between China and India to illustrate this interdependence of freedoms.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen noted that both countries had been working towards developing their economies—China since 1979 and India since 1991.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 2009, Sen published a book called *The Idea of Justice*.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Based on his previous work in welfare economics and social choice theory, but also on his philosophical thoughts, Sen presented his own theory of justice that he meant to be an alternative to the influential modern theories of justice of John Rawls or John Harsanyi.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] However, he still regards institutions and processes as being equally important.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] As an alternative to Rawls's veil of ignorance, Sen chose the thought experiment of an impartial spectator as the basis of his theory of justice.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He also stressed the importance of public discussion (understanding democracy in the sense of John Stuart Mill) and a focus on people's capabilities (an approach that he had co-developed), including the notion of universal human rights, in evaluating various states with regard to justice.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen began his career both as a teacher and a research scholar in the Department of Economics, Jadavpur University as a professor of economics in 1956.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] From 1957 to 1963, Sen served as a fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Between 1960 and 1961, Sen was a visiting professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology in the United States, where he got to know Paul Samuelson, Robert Solow, Franco Modigliani, and Norbert Wiener.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He was also a visiting professor at the University of California, Berkeley (1964–1965) and Cornell University (1978–1984).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He taught as Professor of Economics between 1963 and 1971 at the Delhi School of Economics (where he completed his *magnum opus*, *Collective Choice and Social Welfare*, in 1969).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He was a companion of distinguished economists like Manmohan Singh (ex-Prime Minister of India and a veteran economist responsible for liberalising the Indian economy), K.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] This is a period considered to be a Golden Period in the history of the DSE.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1971, he joined the London School of Economics as a professor of economics, and taught there until 1977.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] From 1977 to 1988, he taught at the University of Oxford, where he was first a professor of economics and fellow of Nuffield College, and then from 1980 the Drummond Professor of Political Economy and a fellow of All Souls College, Oxford.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1985, Sen co-founded the Eva Colorni Trust at the former London Guildhall University in memory of his deceased wife.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1987, Sen joined Harvard as the Thomas W.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Lamont University Professor of Economics.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1998 he was appointed as Master of Trinity College, Cambridge, becoming the first Asian head of an Oxbridge college.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In January 2004, Sen returned to Harvard.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In May 2007, he was appointed chairman of Nalanda Mentor Group to plan the establishment of Nalanda University.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The university was intended to be a revival of Nalanda mahavihara, an ancient educational centre.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He chaired the Social Sciences jury for the Infosys Prize from 2009 to 2011, and the Humanities jury from 2012 to 2018.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] On 19 July 2012, Sen was named the first chancellor of the proposed Nalanda University (NU).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen was criticised as the project suffered due to inordinate delays, mismanagement, and lack of presence of faculty on ground.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] On 20 February 2015, Sen withdrew his candidature for a second term.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He has served as president of the Econometric Society (1984), the International Economic Association (1986–1989), the Indian Economic Association (1989) and the American Economic Association (1994).
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He has also served as president of the Development Studies Association and the Human Development and Capability Association.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He serves as the honorary director of the Academic Advisory Committee of the Center for Human and Economic Development Studies at Peking University in China.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen has been called "the Conscience of the profession" and "the Mother Teresa of Economics" for his work on famine, human development theory, welfare economics, the underlying mechanisms of poverty, gender inequality, and political liberalism.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] However, he denies the comparison to Mother Teresa, saying that he has never tried to follow a lifestyle of dedicated self-sacrifice.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Amartya Sen also added his voice to the campaign against the anti-gay Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen has served as Honorary Chairman of Oxfam, the UK based international development charity, and is now its Honorary Advisor.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen is also a member of the Berggruen Institute's 21st Century Council.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen is an Honorary Fellow of St Edmund's College, Cambridge.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He is also one of the 25 leading figures on the Information and Democracy Commission launched by Reporters Without Borders.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] A 56-minute documentary named *Amartya Sen: A Life Re-examined* directed by Suman Ghosh details his life and work.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] A documentary about Amartya Sen, titled The Argumentative Indian (the title of one of Sen's own books), was released in 2017.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] A 2001 portrait of Sen by Annabel Cullen is in Trinity College's collection.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] A 2003 portrait of Sen hangs in the National Portrait Gallery in London.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 2011, he was present at the *Rabindra Utsab* ceremony at Bangabandhu International Conference Centre (BICC), Bangladesh.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He unveiled the cover of Sruti Gitobitan, a Rabindrasangeet album comprising all the 2222 Tagore songs, brought out by Rezwana Chowdhury Bannya, principal of Shurer Dhara School of Music.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Max Roser said that it was the work of Sen that made him create Our World in Data.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen was critical of Narendra Modi when he was announced as the prime ministerial candidate for the BJP.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In April 2014, he said that Modi would not make a good prime minister.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He conceded later in December 2014 that Modi did give people a sense of faith that things can happen.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In February 2015, Sen opted out of seeking a second term for the chancellor post of Nalanda University, stating that the Government of India was not keen on him continuing in the post.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He regarded the detention of Kashmiri political leaders as "a classical colonial excuse" to prevent backlash against the Indian government's decision and called for a democratic solution that would involve Kashmiri people.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen has spent much of his later life as a political writer and activist.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He has been outspoken about Narendra Modi's leadership in India.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In an interview with *The New York Times*, he claimed that Modi's fearmongering among the Indian people was anti-democratic.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen also wrote an article for *The New York Times* in 2013 documenting the reasons why India trailed behind China in economic development.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He advocated for healthcare reform, because low-income people in India have to deal with exploitative and inadequate private healthcare.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He recommended that India implement the same education policies that Japan did in the late 19th century.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] However, he conceded that there is a tradeoff between democracy and progress in Asia because democracy is a near reality in India and not in China.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In a 1999 article in *The Atlantic*, Sen recommended for India a middle path between the "hard-knocks" development policy that creates wealth at the expense of civil liberties, and radical progressivism that only seeks to protect civil liberties at the expense of development.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Rather than create an entirely new theory for ethical development in Asia, Sen sought to reform the current development model.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 2025, Sen raised concerns about the Special Intensive Revision (SIR) of electoral rolls in Bihar, warning that it could disenfranchise poor and marginalized people if documentation requirements are too strict.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] His first wife was Nabaneeta Dev Sen, an Indian writer and scholar, with whom he had two daughters: Antara, a journalist and publisher, and Nandana, a Bollywood actress.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Their marriage broke up shortly after they moved to London in 1971.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1978 Sen married Eva Colorni, an Italian economist, daughter of Eugenio Colorni and Ursula Hirschmann and niece of Albert O.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The couple had two children, a daughter Indrani, who is a journalist in New York, and a son Kabir, a hip hop artist, MC, and music teacher at Shady Hill School.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 1991, Sen married Emma Georgina Rothschild, who serves as the Jeremy and Jane Knowles Professor of History at Harvard University.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] The Sens have a house in Cambridge, Massachusetts, which is the base from which they teach during the academic year.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] They also have a home in Cambridge, England, where Sen is a Fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge, and Rothschild is a Fellow of Magdalene College.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] He usually spends his winter holidays at his home in Shantiniketan in West Bengal, India, where he used to go on long bike rides until recently.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] Sen has received over 90 honorary degrees from universities around the world.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/amartya-sen] In 2019, London School of Economics announced the creation of the Amartya Sen Chair in Inequality Studies.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] The original building was commissioned as a sanctuary for tuberculosis patients and opened as Nordrach on Dee Hospital in 1900.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] When tuberculosis died down it served as a luxury hotel (when it became "Glen o' Dee"), but was taken over during the Second World War to serve as a billet for troops.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] In 1955 it became a convalescent hospital.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] It reprised its role in contagious diseases when a typhoid epidemic hit nearby Aberdeen in the 1960s, but its last use was as a residential home for the elderly before it closed in 1998.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] The original building was featured on the BBC's *Restoration* programme and, although local people campaigned to have it restored, it continued to sit empty and deteriorating.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] The building was badly damaged by fire on 14 October 2016 with police treating the incident as wilful fire-raising.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] On 14 November 1989 it became a Category A listed building; on 25 November 2016 it was delisted.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] A small modern community hospital staffed by GPs now operates on the site.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] A befriending service was established at the community hospital in 2013 matching older patients ready to be discharged, but lacking confidence to return home, with a volunteer befriender.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] The volunteers then visit the older patients regularly in hospital and at home after discharge, offering on-going emotional and practical support.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] Local GPs reported the service had improved the overall health and wellbeing of their patients and reduced the number of medically unnecessary GP visits.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] Robert Young Keers FRSE was Superintendent of the facility from around 1950 to 1957.
[src:glen-o-dee-hospital/glen-o-dee-hospital] The hospital was destroyed in October 2016 after it was wilfully set on fire by two 13 year old boys.
